He did not answer, for there was no desire in his heart to tell his secret;
                        his experience with Hotep had warned him. Yet the unusual winsomeness of his
                        father's noble love was hard to resist.

"Nay, forgive me!" he said penitently. "So intent
                        was I on thy rescue that I forgot to soften my words. Let it be. It is said;
                        I would it were not true."

"Have it thy way, then, vixen," he exclaimed;
                        "but, remember, I hold a heavy hand above thy head and
                        Hotep's!"

"We hold the Hebrews," was the undisturbed re- ply;
                        "through destruction and plague we have held them. They boast the
                        calamities as sendings from:ieir God. Egypt's afflictions multiply;
                        every resort hath failed us. One is left—to free the slaves and test their
                        boast."

"Alas! what have I done?" she cried. "I am as fit
                        for the brick-fields as Rachel. O, if thou but knew her,
                        Rameses!"

"I know, O Son of Ptah," Kenkenes replied quietly;
                        "but the messenger who knew its contents would suf- fer not
                        disaster or death to stay him in carrying it to thee."
